TY  - JOUR
T1  - Inflation and the Redistribution of Nominal Wealth
AU  - Doepke, Matthias
AU  - Schneider, Martin
Y1  - 2006/12/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/508379
DO  - 10.1086/508379
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1069
EP  - 1097
VL  - 114
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This study quantitatively assesses the effects of inflation through changes in the value of nominal assets. It documents nominal asset positions in the United States across sectors and groups of households and estimates the wealth redistribution caused by a moderate inflation episode. The main losers from inflation are rich, old households, the major bondholders in the economy. The main winners are young, middle?class households with fixed?rate mortgage debt. Besides transferring resources from the old to the young, inflation is a boon for the government and a tax on foreigners. Lately, the amount of U.S. nominal assets held by foreigners has grown dramatically, increasing the potential for a large inflation?induced wealth transfer from foreigners to domestic households.
AB  - This study quantitatively assesses the effects of inflation through changes in the value of nominal assets. It documents nominal asset positions in the United States across sectors and groups of households and estimates the wealth redistribution caused by a moderate inflation episode. The main losers from inflation are rich, old households, the major bondholders in the economy. The main winners are young, middle?class households with fixed?rate mortgage debt. Besides transferring resources from the old to the young, inflation is a boon for the government and a tax on foreigners. Lately, the amount of U.S. nominal assets held by foreigners has grown dramatically, increasing the potential for a large inflation?induced wealth transfer from foreigners to domestic households.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/508379
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/508379
Y2  - 2024/03/19
